            <div class="content__page-desc">
              <h3>Faulty Door Switch</h3>
              <p>
                One of the most common issues with microwave ovens is a faulty
                door switch. When the door switch is broken or malfunctioning,
                the microwave oven may not start or may stop working mid-cycle.
                This issue arises because the microwave relies on door switches
                to ensure the door is properly closed before it can generate
                microwave energy. Fixing this problem often involves replacing
                the faulty switch with a new one. However, if the same problem
                persists, it may indicate an underlying issue with the wiring or
                other components. A qualified technician can diagnose and repair
                this issue to get your appliance back in working order.
              </p>
            </div>

            <div class="content__page-desc">
              <h3>Turntable Not Rotating</h3>
              <p>
                Another frequent problem with microwave ovens is a turntable
                that fails to rotate. This can affect the evenness of cooking,
                leading to hot and cold spots in your food. The issue is often
                related to the turntable motor or the rotating mechanism, which
                may need to be repaired or replaced. Sometimes, the problem
                could be as simple as a misaligned turntable or a broken drive
                bushing. To fix this, you may need to inspect the turntable and
                ensure all components are correctly aligned and functioning. If
                the issue persists, a technician may need to replace the
                turntable motor or other related parts.
              </p>
            </div>

            <div class="content__page-desc">
              <h3>Microwave Not Heating</h3>
              <p>
                A microwave that turns on but doesn’t heat food is a common
                problem often caused by a defective magnetron, high voltage
                diode, or capacitor. These are critical components that generate
                and manage the microwave energy used for cooking. When they
                fail, the microwave can’t produce the necessary heat. Repairing
                this issue usually involves testing and replacing the faulty
                components. Given the high voltage involved, it’s advisable to
                have a qualified technician handle these repairs to avoid any
                safety risks.
              </p>
            </div>

            <div class="content__page-desc">
              <h3>Control Panel Malfunctions</h3>
              <p>
                Control panel issues can range from unresponsive buttons to
                erratic behavior, making it difficult to set cooking times or
                select functions. This can be caused by worn-out buttons, a
                faulty control board, or issues with the membrane switch.
                Replacing the entire control panel or specific components within
                it can resolve these issues. However, diagnosing the exact cause
                may require expert knowledge and specialized tools. If your
                microwave's control panel is malfunctioning, it’s best to
                consult a technician for a precise fix.
              </p>
            </div>

            <div class="content__page-desc">
              <h3>Blown Fuse</h3>
              <p>
                A blown fuse is another common issue that can prevent your
                microwave from powering on. This can happen due to a power surge
                or an internal fault within the microwave. The fuse acts as a
                safety device to protect the appliance from electrical damage.
                Replacing a blown fuse is generally straightforward, but it’s
                essential to identify the root cause to prevent it from
                happening again. This may involve inspecting other components
                like the transformer and capacitors to ensure they are
                functioning correctly.
              </p>
            </div>

            <div class="content__page-desc">
              <h3>Overheating</h3>
              <p>
                Microwaves can sometimes overheat, causing them to shut down as
                a safety measure. This can be due to a faulty cooling fan,
                clogged air vents, or overheating components like the magnetron.
                To address this, you should check the air vents and clean them
                if they are blocked. If the cooling fan is not working, it may
                need to be replaced. Ensuring that your microwave is
                well-ventilated and not covered during operation can also help
                prevent overheating issues.
              </p>
            </div>

            <div class="content__page-desc">
              <h3>Light Not Working</h3>
              <p>
                If the interior light of your microwave is not working, it could
                be due to a blown bulb or a faulty light socket. While this
                issue doesn’t affect the microwave’s cooking performance, it can
                be inconvenient. Replacing the bulb is usually a simple task,
                but if the light socket is the problem, you may need
                professional help to fix it. Testing the light circuit can help
                identify the exact cause and allow for the appropriate repairs
                to be made.
              </p>
            </div>

            <div class="content__page-desc">
              <h3>Sparking Inside the Microwave</h3>
              <p>
                Sparking inside the microwave is a serious issue that can be
                caused by metal objects, such as utensils or aluminum foil,
                being left inside during cooking. It can also result from a
                damaged waveguide cover or a faulty stirrer. If you notice
                sparks, immediately stop the microwave and inspect the interior.
                Remove any metallic objects and check for damage to the
                waveguide cover. Replacing a damaged cover can prevent further
                sparking and ensure safe operation. If the problem persists,
                consult a technician for a thorough inspection and repair.
              </p>
            </div>
